        "avatar_template": "https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/j/f475e1/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2022-03-31T07:40:13.614Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Currently we don\u2019t have an official way of doing this but here are my thoughts how I would approach this (not tested):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>I would set the <code>skip</code> option to true for this cluster <a href=\"https://github.com/FoundationDB/fdb-kubernetes-operator/blob/main/docs/cluster_spec.md#foundationdbclusterspec\" class=\"inline-onebox\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">fdb-kubernetes-operator/cluster_spec.md at main \u00b7 FoundationDB/fdb-kubernetes-operator \u00b7 GitHub</a>, this basically means the operator won\u2019t do any action on it.</li>\n<li>Now you can delete all Pods, the PVCs will stay available.</li>\n<li>You could leave the operator and the cluster spec in that state and once you need the cluster again change <code>skip</code> to <code>false</code> and the operator should bring back those Pods.</li>\n<li>Once all Pods are up and running (and you didn\u2019t use services) you probably have to run <a href=\"https://github.com/FoundationDB/fdb-kubernetes-operator/blob/main/docs/manual/debugging.md#coordinators-getting-new-ips\" class=\"inline-onebox\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">fdb-kubernetes-operator/debugging.md at main \u00b7 FoundationDB/fdb-kubernetes-operator \u00b7 GitHub</a> to fix the connection string.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I think all of those steps should work without a problem and you probably should be able to write a script/automaton around it. Like I said I didn\u2019t test those steps so you want to test those steps in a test cluster.</p>",
